ic contingencies and other contingencies, such as legal, regulatory, market access, political, social license, internal and external approvals and commitment to project finance and development timing.  As many of these factors are extremely difficult to quantify, the chance of development is uncertain and must be used with caution.  The chance of development was estimated to be 80 percent for both Crude Oil types and 5 percent for the Natural Gas.<ref name=\"Dec2017Reserves\" /></sup>\n\n<sup>(3)The Atrush Field contains crude oil of variable density even within a single reservoir unit and as such the actual split between Light/Medium Oil and Heavy Oil is uncertain.<ref name=\"Dec2017Reserves\" /></sup>\n\n<sup>(4)Shamaran gross reserves are based on the Shamaran\u2019s 20.1 percent working interest share of the property gross reserves.<ref name=\"Dec2017Reserves\" /></sup>\n\n<sup>(5)Shamaran net reserves are based on Shmaran's share of total Cost and Profit Revenues.<ref name=\"Dec2017Reserves\" /></sup>\n\n==Atrush Map==\n[[File:Atrush Block.jpg|thumb|999px|Atrush Field from space with the block boundary in red, taken September 4, 2018 by the European Space Agency - ESA produced from ESA remote sensing data image processed by SNAP Desktop 6.0.3|none|Atrush Map]]\nAtrush Field from space with the block boundary in red, taken September 4, 2018 by the European Space Agency - ESA produced from ESA remote sensing data image processed by SNAP Desktop 6.0.3\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Portal|Iraq|Energy}}\n\n[[Category:Oil fields of Iraq]]\n[[Category:Duhok]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Oilfield in Iraqi Kurdistan}}\n{{Infobox oil field\n| name        = Atrush Field\n| image       = \n| caption     = \n| location_map       = Iraq\n| location_map_width = \n| location_map_text  = \n| coordinates = {{coord|36|51|48|N|43|27|1|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| coordinates_ref    = <ref>http://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/i/pdf/CorporatePresentation_Sept2012.pdf</ref>\n| country     = [[Iraq]]\n| region      = [[Dohuk]]\n| location    = [[Sheikan district]]\n| block       = \n| offonshore  = Onshore\n| operators   = \n[[TAQA]] (47.4%) \n| partners    = \n[[Kurdistan Regional Government]] (25%)\n\n[[ShaMaran Petroleum Corp.]] (27.6%)\n\n| contractors = \n| discovery   = April 13th 2011<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com\">{{Cite web |url=http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-announces-major-oil-discovery-at-atrush-p-tsx-venture-snm-201104130689394001 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-02-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131001201837/http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-announces-major-oil-discovery-at-atrush-p-tsx-venture-snm-201104130689394001 |archive-date=2013-10-01 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| start_development = \n| start_production = July 3rd, 2017<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">{{Cite web |url=http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/oil-production-in-atrush-started-tsx-venture-snm-201707031098541001 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-07-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170807161616/http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/oil-production-in-atrush-started-tsx-venture-snm-201707031098541001 |archive-date=2017-08-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n| peak_year   =\n| abandonment =\n| peak_of_production_oil_bbl/d =\n| peak_of_production_oil_tpy =\n| peak_of_production_gas_mmcuft/d =\n| peak_of_production_gas_mmscm/d =\n| peak_of_production_gas_bcm/y =\n| oil_production_bbl/d = 45000 \n| oil_production_tpy =\n| production_year_oil = \n| production_gas_mmcuft/d =\n| production_gas_mmscm/d =\n| production_gas_bcm/y =\n| production_year_gas =\n| est_oil_bbl =  296  \n| est_oil_t   = \n| recover_oil_bbl = 102.7 \n| recover_oil_t   =\n| est_gas_bft =\n| est_gas_bcm =\n| recover_gas_bft =\n| recover_gas_bcm =\n| formations  = Jurassic fractured carbonate<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.com\">https://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/3675/2017-05-15-cp.pdf</ref>\n}}\n'''Atrush Field''' is a Jurassic fractured carbonate oilfield near [[Dohuk]], [[Iraqi Kurdistan]]. It was discovered by the Consortium of General Exploration Partners. As of March 12, 2013 the [[Kurdistan Regional Government]] (KRG) has exercised its option to acquire a 25% Government Interest of the Atrush Field according to the PSC contract.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\">{{Cite web |url=http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-2012-year-end-financial-and-operating-res-tsx-venture-snm-201303150860336001 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-03-29 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130331005149/http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-2012-year-end-financial-and-operating-res-tsx-venture-snm-201303150860336001 |archive-date=2013-03-31 |url-status=dead }}</ref> <br>\n<br>\nGeneral Exploration Partners (GEP) held 80% of Atrush and was in cooperation with Aspect Energy International, who owned 2/3 of GEP, thus Aspect Energy International had a share of 53,2%. Aspect Energy International sold its interest in GEP to [[TAQA]] for $600 mln,<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2013/01/02/kurdistan-taqa-acquisition-idUKL5E9C215720130102?irpc=932 | title=TAQA buys stake in Iraqi Kurdistan oil block for $600 mln| newspaper=Reuters| date=2013-01-02}}</ref> which basically transferred Aspect's interest in GEP to TAQA. Shamaran's interest remained at 26,8% of Atrush, and the remaining 20% is held by Marathon Oil.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.iraq-businessnews.com/tag/abu-dhabi-national-energy-company-taqa/ | title=ShaMaran acquires Larger Stake in Atrush}}</ref> <br>\n<br>\nIn June, 2018 Shamaran Petroleum announced that it intends to purchase Marathon Petroleum's 15% share of the Atrush Block.,<ref>https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/32005/2018-06-04-nr-snm.pdf</ref> with effect from Jan 1, 2018.  ShaMaran will acquire all shares of MOKDV - Marathon\u2019s Dutch subsidiary for USD 63m. ShaMaran will then sell 7.5% working interest to Taqa for USD 33m. The sale is expected to close in the first quarter of 2019.<ref name=\"Jan2019\">https://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/72240/190114_corporate_presentation_january_2019.pdf</ref>\n<br><br>\n\nOil began flowing through the Atrush Central Production Facility on July 3, 2017.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> In September 2017, an agreement for the sale of Atrush oil was signed between TAQA, its partners and the KRG. Under the agreement, the KRG will buy oil exported from the Atrush field by pipeline at the Atrush block boundary.  The quality of the oil will force a price adjustment of approximately $16/bbl lower than the dated Brent oil price. All local and international transportation costs will be an additional fee. This discount is based on the principles similar to other oil sales agreements in the Kurdistan Region of Iraq.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\">{{Cite web |url=http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-announces-atrush-oil-sales-agreement-signed-tsx-venture-snm-201709291102921001 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-10-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171002192604/http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-announces-atrush-oil-sales-agreement-signed-tsx-venture-snm-201709291102921001 |archive-date=2017-10-02 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Atrush Field Naming Conventions==\nIn 2014 after a meeting of the Atrush Management Committee and the [http://mnr.krg.org/index.php/en KRG Ministry of Natural Resources] changes in terminology used with respect to activity in the Atrush Field were made:<ref name=\"Pareto\">http://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/i/pdf/2014-Sep-Pareto-Securities-Oil-Gas-Conference.pdf</ref>\n* \u201cAtrush Block\u201d, \u201cAtrush PSC\u201d & \u201cAtrush Field\u201d were unchanged.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* The structure (previously referred to as the \u201cAtrush structure\u201d) is renamed after the Chiya Khere mountain, i.e. the Chiya Khere structure.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* All production facilities will be known as the Chiya Khere facilities.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* Future wells will remain sequential but will be referred to as \u201cChiya Khere\u201d, short-form \u201cCK\u201d, commencing with well #5.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* Well pads will be known as Chamanke A, B, etc.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />  \n* Historic wells, AT-1 through AT-4, will retain their original nomenclature.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n\n==Wells==\n\n===Atrush-1 (AT-1) Well===\n\nAtrush-1 (AT-1) well was successfully spudded on October 5, 2010. The well had a natural flow of 6,393 barrels of oil per day. General Exploration Partners discovered 726 meters of oil column and 120 meter netpay.  The well has since been  permanently abandoned <ref name=\"Jan2019\" /><ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/s/Atrush.asp?ReportID=420604 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2013-02-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130303205451/http://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/s/Atrush.asp?ReportID=420604 |archive-date=2013-03-03 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Atrush-2 (AT-2) Well===\n\nAtrush-2 (AT-2) well was successfully spudded on May 23, 2012. The well had a flow of 42212 barrels of oil per day using a [[Submersible pump]],<ref>https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/09/13/idUS200698+13-Sep-2012+PRN20120913</ref> estimated to have been the highest flow ever in [[Iraqi Kurdistan]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.oilandgasmiddleeast.com/article-10614-shamaran-strikes-it-rich-at-atrush-block|title=ShaMaran strikes it rich at Atrush block|website=Oil & Gas Middle East}}</ref> The design of the DST Program, as well as the permanent completion, was managed by Daniel Riedel, Richard Sharpe, Damon Yarshenko, and Wes Whitman with key execution support provided by core contractors. AT-2 was completed for production in Q3 of 2016.<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.com\" />\n\n===Atrush-3 (AT-3) Well===\n\nAtrush-3 (AT-3) well was believed the well spudded on the 26th of March 2013 but there is no information confirming this for now.<ref name=\"ReferenceB\"/>\n\n====AT-3 Well Summary====\n* In December 2018 the well was worked over as a heavy oil production well and is now ready for the heavy oil extended well test.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" />\n\n===Atrush-4 (AT-4) Well===\nDrilled in 2014, Atrush-4 (AT-4) well is the second well to be drilled in support of the Phase One Facility.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n\n====AT-4 Well Summary====\n* High-angle deviated well.  82\u00b0 was the maximum hole angle.  This demonstrated that the field could be developed, using directional wells in the face of extremely rugged terrain.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* The well was drilled from the AT-1 pad, which is correctly known as Chamanke-A.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* The Jurassic reservoir is approximately 72m higher than when it was encountered in AT-1.<ref name=\"Pareto\" /> \n* Two limited well tests were performed for fluid samples.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* The combined rate of fluid production was over {{convert|9000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day of 26\u00b0API oil.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* There wasn't an indication of a gas cap.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* An [http://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/Terms/w/well_interference_testing.aspx/ interference test] was also conducted.  The test demonstrated instantaneous pressure communication with AT-2.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* AT-4 was suspended as Phase One Facility producer.<ref name=\"Pareto\" />\n* AT-4 was completed for production in Q3 of 2016.<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.com\"/>\n* Clean-up attempts were made during 2018, but resulted in disappointing productivity the well is now awaiting work-over for a smaller pump.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" />\n\n===Chiya Khere-5 (CK-5) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-5 (CK-5) well<ref name=\"Pareto\" /> was completed in Q3 of 2015.<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.com\"/>\n\n===Chiya Khere-6 (CK-6) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-6 (CK-6) Phase 2 appraisal well has a total depth of 2,105 metres. The TAQA-operated well reached TD on November 5, 2014, after 36 operational days.  Part of the eastern part of the Atrush block the well is located on the Chamanke C pad. This pad is also the location of AT-3.  CK-6 is a directional well, drilled in SSE direction from the surface.  CK-6 encountered the Jurassic age reservoir at a higher elevation (\u2248139 metres) than the nearby AT-3 well.<ref name=\"CK-6Flow\">{{Cite web | url=http://www.oilandgastechnology.net/upstream-news/taqa-flows-oil-ck-6-well-kurdistan | title=Taqa flows oil at CK-6 well in Kurdistan &#124; Oil and Gas Technology}}</ref> As of January 2019 the well is awaiting a work over to become an observation well during the heavy oil extended well test of AT-3.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /><br>\nThe well was recompleted in February 2019 and came online for production in May 2019 at {{convert|4500|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day.<ref>{{cite web |title=ShaMaran Second Quarter 2019 Update |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/news/shamaran-second-quarter-2019-financial-and-operati-122715/ |website=ShaMaran Petroleum |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Well Testing====\n{{block indent |1=DST #1<ref name=\"CK-6Flow\" />\n* Formation:  Alan<ref name=\"CK-6Flow\" />\n* Perforated interval:  12 metres<ref name=\"CK-6Flow\" /> \n* Using an Electric Submersible Pump (ESP) and [http://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/Terms/n/nitrogen_lift.aspx/ nitrogen lift] the heavy oil was produced at a low rate.<ref name=\"CK-6Flow\" />   \n* The test interval was the deepest from which oil has been recovered.  At -460 m below sea level, the CK-6 oil was found to be almost 200 m deeper than the oil recovered from the equivalent reservoir in well AT-2.<ref name=\"CK-6Flow\" />\n* The viscosity of the recovered oil was lower than the oil from AT-2.<ref name=\"CK-6Flow\" />}}\n\n===Chiya Khere-7 (CK-7) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-7 (CK-7) appraisal and development well drilling operations commenced prior to September 19, 2017. CK-7 is located in the central area of the Atrush Block. The producing well, AT-2, is approximately 3 kilometres to the east, while AT-3 is 3.5 kilometres to the west. The well is most likely being drilled from the Chamanke E pad. The objectives are to add another producing well by appraising the Mus formation's commercial potential and to reduce the uncertainty in determining the depth of the medium to the heavy oil transition zone. The well is expected to reach the 1,575 metre Total Depth within 52 days, using the Romfor 25 drilling rig.<ref name=\"CK-7\">{{Cite web |url=http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-atrush-development-update-spud-of-ck-7-tsx-venture-snm-201709191102449001 |title=Archived copy |access-date=2017-09-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920191500/http://shamaranpetroleum.mwnewsroom.com/press-releases/shamaran-atrush-development-update-spud-of-ck-7-tsx-venture-snm-201709191102449001 |archive-date=2017-09-20 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Chiya Khere-8 (CK-8) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-8 (CK-8) well<ref name=\"Pareto\" /> was completed in Q3 of 2015<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.com\"/>\n\n===Chiya Khere-9 (CK-9) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-9 (CK-9) water disposal well, was drilled successfully as planned and is ready for water injection.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" />\n\n===Chiya Khere-10 (CK-10) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-10 (CK-10) well was drilled in June 2018<ref name=\"June2018\">https://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/32011/2018-06-cp-snm.pdf</ref> and tied into the facility in July 2018.<ref name=\"Sept2018\">https://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/49436/180902-corporate-presentation-september-2018.pdf</ref>\n\n===Chiya Khere-11 (CK-11) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-11 (CK-11) is a deviated infill production well, located on the Chamanke-G pad, that was [https://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/en/Terms/s/spud.aspx spud] on 3 January 2019, the [https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007/s12517-014-1651-0 Sargelu] formation is the target.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /><br>\nThe well was drilled to its final depth by mid-March, came online for production on May 10, 2019, produced at {{convert|5500|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day (during July 2019)<ref>{{cite web |title=Shamaran Second Quarter 2019 Update |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/news/shamaran-second-quarter-2019-financial-and-operati-122715/ |website=ShaMaran Petroleum |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> and increased to {{convert|8500|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q3 ShaMaran petroleum corp. Financial Report |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5129/2019q3snm.pdf |website=ShaMaran petroleum corp. |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chiya Khere-12 (CK-12) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-12 (CK-12) is a 2,400 metre deviated infill production well, located on the Chamanke-E pad<ref>{{cite web |title=Q3 ShaMaran petroleum corp. Financial Report |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5129/2019q3snm.pdf |website=ShaMaran petroleum corp. |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> that was [https://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/en/Terms/s/spud.aspx spud] in 2019, the well was brought on production in Q3 2019.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/news/shamaran-third-quarter-2019-financial-and-operatin-122722/|title=Welcome to ShaMaran Petroleum Corp. Website|website=ShaMaran Petroleum Corp.}}</ref><br>\nCK-12 was drilled to its final depth at the end of May 19, 2019, where the reservoir was found to be 25 metres deeper than the prognosis indicated. CK-12 well was left cased and suspended until a workover rig was used to complete CK-12 in July 2019. Production commenced on August 10, 2019. CK-12 is currently producing at a rate of {{convert|2000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day from the Mus Formation.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q3 ShaMaran petroleum corp. Financial Report |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5129/2019q3snm.pdf |website=ShaMaran petroleum corp. |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Chiya Khere-13 (CK-13) Well===\n\nChiya Khere-13 (CK-13) located on Chamanke-E, is a 2,340m deviated infill production well that was [https://www.glossary.oilfield.slb.com/en/Terms/s/spud.aspx spud] in June 2019<ref>{{cite web |title=Shamaran Second Quarter 2019 Update |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/news/shamaran-second-quarter-2019-financial-and-operati-122715/ |website=ShaMaran Petroleum |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>, drilled to TD by August 19, 2019 and brought on production on September 18, 2019 at a rate of {{convert|6000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day. This well also encounted the targer formation at a lower than expected depth, 23 metres lower to be exact.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q3 ShaMaran petroleum corp. Financial Report |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5129/2019q3snm.pdf |website=ShaMaran petroleum corp. |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> The failure by TAQA's development geologist, well operation geologist and the geological manager to accurately forecast formation depths is rumoured to be a sore point within the partnership.<br>\n\n===Chiya Khere-14 (CK-14) Well===\nNo mention of CK-14 has ever been publicly announced.\n\n===Chiya Khere-15 (CK-15) Well===\nChiya Khere-15 (CK-15) is a deviated infill production well at the Chamanke-G drilling location. The well was spudded on October 5, 2019 and is targeted to come online in December\n2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q3 ShaMaran petroleum corp. Financial Report |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5129/2019q3snm.pdf |website=ShaMaran petroleum corp. |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n  \n=== Heavy Oil Extended Well Test  (HOEWT) ===\nDuring 2018 the operator installed heavy oil well testing equipment. The equipment will provide {{convert|5000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day additional processing capacity at the Chamanke C pad, where AT-3 is located. Heavy oil production to should begin in February 2019.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /><br>\nIn fact, the HOEWT was delayed until mid-April.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shamaran Second Quarter 2019 Update |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/news/shamaran-second-quarter-2019-financial-and-operati-122715/ |website=ShaMaran Petroleum |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>, the well was brought on production in Q3 2019.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n===Future wells===\n\nDrill and Complete three to four more production wells (including CK-11, CK-12, CK-13 and CK-15) during 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Q3 ShaMaran petroleum corp. Financial Report |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5129/2019q3snm.pdf |website=ShaMaran petroleum corp. |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Producing Wells===\nThe five producing wells: Atrush-2, (\u201cAT-2\u201d) Chiya Khere-5 (\u201cCK-5\u201d), Chiya Khere-7 (\u201cCK-7\u201d), Chiya Khere-8 (\u201cCK-8\u201d) and Chiya Khere-10 (\u201cCK-10\u201d).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/news/shamaran-announces-financial-and-operating-results-122709/|title=Welcome to ShaMaran Petroleum Corp. Website|website=ShaMaran Petroleum Corp.}}</ref> In 2019, Chiya Khere-6 (\u201cCK-6\u201d), Chiya Khere-11 (\u201cCK-11\u201d), Chiya Khere-12 (\"CK-12\"), and Chiya Khere-13 (\"CK-13\") have also been added as production wells.<ref name=\"auto\"/> In December 2019, Chiya Khere-15 (\"CK-15\") was also listed as a production well.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/news/shamaran-atrush-update-122723//|title=ShaMaran Atrush Update. Website|website=ShaMaran Petroleum Corp.}}</ref>\n\n===Wells Pads===\n* Chamanke A<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /> Construction completed, AT-1, AT-4, CK-5 and CK-8 were drilled here.\n* Chamanke B<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /> Construction completed, AT-2 was drilled here, the pad is commonly referred to as PF-1 as it is the home of the Production Facility.\n* Chamanke C<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /> Construction completed, AT-3 and CK-6 were drilled here. This is where the heavy oil extended well test will occur.\n* Chamanke D<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.com\" /> Proposed location is 2&nbsp;km west of Chamanke A\n* Chamanke E<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /> Construction completed, the location is 2&nbsp;km east of Chamanke B and is the site of CK-7, CK-10, CK-12 and CK-13\n* Chamanke F<ref name=\"shamaranpetroleum.com\" /> Proposed location is east of Chamanke C\n* Chamanke G<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /> Construction completed, the location is northeast of Chamanke B and CK-9, CK-11 and CK-15 were drilled from here.\n\n==Facilities==\nA {{convert|30,000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day Phase 1 facilities has been completed.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> As of September 29, 2017 the facility has achieved a regular daily export of more than {{convert|22,000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil equivalent.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\"/> Facility production is expected to increase to {{convert|30,000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil equivalent per day during 2017.<ref name=\"ReferenceD\"/> <br>\nIn June 2018 Shamaran Petroleum reported a partial blockage of the production facility's heat exchanger. Sediment samples were analyzed and it was determined that the blockage was caused by salt. The most probable source of the salt might be drilling fluid losses from the drilling of CK-5 and AT-2.  The heat exchanger was cleaned. A trial process of injecting freshwater at the CK-5 wellhead and separating saltwater out at the production facility's separator have significantly reduced the quantity of salt in the crude to be processed for export.  <br>\nAs of June 2018, approximately {{convert|20,000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day of processed oil is being exported.  Water injection at the wellhead will continue while gradually increasing production as the field personnel closely monitor the facility. Water injection is limited due to the small daily disposal capacity, once the CK-9 water disposal well is completed in the second half of 2018, the capacity will increase.<ref>https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/32941/2018-06-08-nr-snm.pdf</ref> The average daily production for 2018 was about {{convert|22,200|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day, the rate at the end of December 2018, was {{convert|27,500|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /> <br>\nDuring 2019, debottlenecking the {{convert|30,000|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day facility will occur.<ref name=\"Jan2019\" /><br><br>\n\nAverage production for the month of November was {{convert|43,360|oilbbl|m3}} of oil per day<ref>https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5156/shamaran_petroleum_corp__shamaran_atrush_update.pdf</ref>\n\n==Pipeline==\n* Pipeline project has been completed<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">http://www.shamaranpetroleum.com/i/pdf/2017-09-11-CP.pdf</ref> \n* The pipeline is made up of 4 sections.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> \n** A {{convert|10|inch|cm|order=flip}} Spur line from the Phase 1 facility to the Intermediate pigging and pressure reduction station \n** A {{convert|12|inch|cm|order=flip}} Spur line from the Intermediate pigging and pressure reduction station to the southern Atrush block boundary\n** A {{convert|12|inch|cm|order=flip}} Feeder line from the southern Atrush block boundary to the Shaikan block's south boundary\n** A {{convert|36|inch|cm|order=flip}} Feeder line from the Shaikan block's south boundary to the Kurdish Export Pipeline.\n\n==Monthly Production Data<ref name=\"Jan2019\" />==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date \n! Volume ([[Barrel_(unit)#Oil barrel|bbl]]/d)\n! Volume ([[cubic metre|m<sup>3</sup>]]/d)\n! Comment\n|-\n| July 2017 || {{convert|4800|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| August 2017 || {{convert|18,300|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| September 2017 || {{convert|21,400|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| October 2017 || {{convert|13,300|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || Facility shut down to address production constraints\n|-\n| November 2017 || {{convert|25,400|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| December 2017 || {{convert|26,300|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| January 2018 || {{convert|26,600|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| February 2018 || {{convert|23,900|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| March 2018 || {{convert|20,200|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || Back-produced salt plugs facilities\n|-\n| April 2018 || {{convert|11,900|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| May 2018 || {{convert|15,100|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| June 2018 || {{convert|20,100|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| July 2018 || {{convert|19,100|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || Shut down to tie-in CK-7, CK-10\n|-\n| August 2018 || {{convert|21,400|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || Frequent pipeline outages\n|-\n| September 2018 || {{convert|24,500|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || Flushed stripper column\n|-\n| October 2018 || {{convert|26,800|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| November 2018 || {{convert|28,200|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| December 2018 || {{convert|27,500|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || CK-10 ESP failure \n|-\n| January 2019 || {{convert|26,900|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| February 2019 || {{convert|23,500|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || 7day Export Pipeline Shutdown\n|-\n| March 2019 ||  {{convert|28,100|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || \n|-\n| April 2019 ||  {{convert|29,000|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} ||\n|-\n| May 2019 ||  {{convert|28,600|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || Reboiler Flushing and CK-8 ESP Failure\n|-\n| June 2019 ||  {{convert|27,100|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}} || CK-8 ESP Replacement \n|-\n| July 2019 ||  {{convert|33,900|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}}<ref>{{cite web |title=ShaMaran Petroleum Q2 results |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/4957/2019q2.pdf |website=ShaMaran Petroleum |accessdate=12 December 2019}}</ref> || CK-8 ESP Online\n|-\n| August 2019 ||  {{convert|35,300|oilbbl|m3|disp=table}}<ref>{{cite web |title=ShaMaran Corporate Presentation September 2019 |url=https://shamaranpetroleum.com/site/assets/files/5119/snm-corporate-prese