}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n| bodystyle        = \n}}\n'''[[Joint stock company#Joint Stock Companies in Russia|OAO]] \"TMK\"''' ({{lang-ru|OAO \u0422\u0440\u0443\u0431\u043d\u0430\u044f \u041c\u0435\u0442\u0430\u043b\u043b\u0443\u0440\u0433\u0438\u0447\u0435\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u041a\u043e\u043c\u043f\u0430\u043d\u0438\u044f|Trubnaya Metallurgicheskaya Kompaniya|Pipe Metallurgical Co., OJSC}}) ({{MICEX-RTS|TRMK}}) is a leading global manufacturer and supplier of [[steel pipe]]s for the oil and gas industry, operating 28 production sites in the United States, Russia, Canada, [[Romania]], [[Oman]], [[UAE]], and [[Kazakhstan]] and two R&D centers in Russia and the United States. \nHeadquarters \u2013 [[Moscow]] (Russia), [[Houston]] (USA).\n\n== History ==\nTMK was established in 2001.\n\nIn 2002 TMK incorporated Volzhsky Pipe Plant, [[Seversky Pipe Plant]] and Sinarsky Pipe Plant. A Trade House TMK representative office was opened in [[Baku]] ([[Azerbaijan]]).\n\nIn 2003 a new TMK subsidiary, TMK-Kazakhstan, was established.\n\nIn 2004 TMK incorporated Taganrog Metallurgical Works.\n\nIn 2005 TMK established and incorporated TMK Global, a representative office was opened in [[Beijing]] (China). CJSC TMK was reorganized into an Open Joint Stock Company.\n\nIn 2006 \u0422\u041c\u041a made [[IPO]] of its GDRs on the [[London Stock Exchange]]. TMK incorporated the Romanian mills TMK-Artrom and TMK-Resita, and the Russian Orsky Machine Building Plant. The TMK Middle East trading subsidiary was created the same year.\n\nIn 2007 TMK acquired oilfield service companies including Truboplast, TMK NGS-Nizhnevartovsk, and TMK NGS-Buzuluk, as well as the Russian Research Institute for the Tube and Pipe Industries (RosNITI), Russia's largest pipe industry research institute. TMK-CPW, a joint venture between TMK and Corinth Pipeworks, and \u0422\u041c\u041a-Premium Service were established. TMK's shares began trading on the [[MICEX]] Stock Exchange. Additionally, \u0422\u041c\u041a opened representative offices in [[Turkmenistan]] and [[Singapore]].\n\n2008 was marked by the acquisition of US pipe assets and the creation of the American division - TMK IPSCO. The Company also established TMK Oilfield Services and acquired TMK-Kaztrubprom (Kazakhstan).\n\nIn 2009 the TMK European Division was created. It includes TMK Europe, TMK Italia, TMK-Artrom, TMK-Resita.\n\nIn 2010 TMK-INOX became a joint venture between TMK and RUSNANO, it coordinates production and sales of precision stainless pipes. TMK ADRs began trading on the [[OTCQX]] International Premier trading platform in the US.\n\nIn 2011 TMK representative office in [[Uzbekistan]] was opened.\n\nIn 2012 the new Research & Development Center in [[Houston]] ([[Texas]], United States) was commissioned and the Trade House TMK subsidiary in [[Orsk]] (Orenburg region) was opened. TMK acquired 55% of Gulf International Pipe Industry L.L.C. (GIPI) located in [[Oman]] and established a service joint venture with EMDAD in [[Abu Dhabi]], the [[United Arab Emirates]].\n\nIn 2013 TMK acquired pipe services and precision manufacturing assets incorporated into OFSi company (Houston, USA).\n\n== Heads ==\n[[Dmitry Pumpyansky]] \u2013 Chairman of the Board of Directors, Alexander Shiryaev - CEO.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tmk-group.com/bod|title=Board of Directors|first=|last=http://www.portalmaster.ru|date=|website=www.tmk-group.com|accessdate=28 September 2018}}</ref>\n\n== Profile ==\nTMK plants produce almost the entire range of existing pipes used in the oil-and-gas sector, the chemical and petrochemical industries, energy and machine-building, construction and municipal housing, shipbuilding, aviation and aerospace, and agriculture.\n\nTMK pipes are manufactured from carbon, stainless, and heat and cold-resistant steels, nickel alloys.\n\nTMK delivers its products along with an extensive package of services in heat treating, protective coating, premium connections threading, warehousing and pipe repairing.\n\nTMK's global market presence is supported by its extensive international distribution network. Sales are made through TMK Trade House and a number of other distributors. TMK supplies products to more than 80 countries around the world. In addition to direct sales, the Company's products are distributed by more than 100 official dealers in Russia and the CIS.\n\nTMK's main markets are Russia, the United States, the [[Middle East]], [[Europe]], [[North Africa]], [[South Asia|South]] and [[Southeast Asia]], and the CIS.\n\n== Production and operation subsidiaries ==\n\n=== Production ===\n\n'''TMK Russian Division'''\n\n* Volzhsky Pipe Plant ([[Volzhsky, Volgograd Oblast|Volzhsky]],<ref>[https://www.bloomberg.com/research/stocks/private/snapshot.asp?privcapid=10078719 Company Overview of Volzhsky Pipe Plant], ''Bloomberg Business''.</ref> Russia) - since 2001\n* Seversky Pipe Plant ([[Polevskoy]], Russia) - since 2002\n* Sinarsky Pipe Plant ([[Kamensk-Uralsky]], Russia) - since 2002\n* Taganrog Metallurgical Works ([[Taganrog]], Russia) - since 2002\n* TMK-Kaztrubprom ([[Uralsk]], [[Republic of Kazakhstan]]) \u2013 since 2008\n* TMK-INOX (Kamensk-Uralsky, Russia) \u2013 since 2010\n* TMK-CPW ([[Polevskoy]], Russia) \u2013 since 2007\n\n'''TMK American Division'''\n\n* \u0422MK-IPSCO (USA) \u2013 since 2008\n* Ambridge (Ambridge, Pennsylvania) \n* Baytown (Baytown, Texas) \n* Blytheville (Blytheville, Arkansas) \n* Brookfield (Brookfield, Ohio) \n* Camanche (Camanche, Iowa) \n* Catoosa (Catoosa, Oklahoma) \n* Geneva (Geneva, Nebraska) \n* Houston (Houston, Texas) \n* Koppel (Koppel, Pennsylvania) \n* Midland/Odessa (Odessa, Texas) \n* Wilder (Wilder, Kentucky)  \n* Edmonton (Alberta, Canada)\n \n'''TMK European Division'''\n\n* TMK-Artrom (Slatina, Romania) \u2013 since 2006  \n* TMK-Resita (Resita, Romania) \u2013 since 2006\n\n'''TMK Middle East Division'''\n\nTMK GIPI (Oman) \u2013 since 2011\n\n=== Services ===\n\n* TMK-Premium Service (Moscow, Russia)\n* TMK Oilfield Services (Moscow, Russia)\n* Orsky Machine Building Plant (Orsk, Russia)\n* Truboplast (Ekaterinburg, Russia)\n* TMK NGS-Nizhnevartovsk (Nizhnevartovsk, Russia)\n* TMK NGS \u2013 Buzuluk (Buzuluk, Russia)\n* Threading&Mechanical Key Premium LLC (Abu Dhabi, the United Arab Emirates)\n* OFSi (Houston, USA)\n\n== R & D ==\nRussian Research Institute for the Tube and Pipe Industries (RosNITI) in Chelyabiinsk (Russia) was established in 2007.\nR&D center in Houston (Texas) was opened in 2012.\n\n== Clients ==\nTMK's clients include such leading Russian and foreign companies as [[Rosneft]], [[Gazprom]], [[Transneft]], [[Lukoil]], [[Surgutneftegas]], [[Shell Oil Company|Shell]], Total, [[Occidental Petroleum]], [[Anadarko Petroleum]], [[Saudi Aramco]], [[AGIP]], [[Wintershall]], [[ONGC]], KOC, [[Repsol]] and others.\n\n== Sponsorship ==\nRussia-based entities provide support to orphanages, educational and medical institutions and finance sport teams.\n\nIn the [[Urals Federal District]] accommodating two TMK entities, charity programmes are run through the corporate charitable foundation Sinara, a professional operator. This facilitates partnership with civic institutions through grant competitions.\n\nTo promote sports, TMK sponsors:\n* the Russian Ski-Jumping and Nordic Combined Federation;\n* a number of professional sports clubs, including: the Ural Football Club of the [[Russian Premier League]]; the Sinara mini-football club in [[Yekaterinburg]], a two-time champion in Russia; the Dinamo Women's Handball Club in [[Volgograd]], an eleven-time champion in Russia; TAGMET tennis club in [[Taganrog]];\n* amateur teams representing TMK entities competing in various sports, including children's and youth sports.\n\nAlso Dmitry Pumpyanskiy is a member of the Council of trustees of the \u201cRussian Olympic Foundation\u201d.\n\nTMK European Division acted as the main sponsor of Russian Culture Days 2013 in [[Bucharest]] dedicated to the 135th Anniversary of diplomatic relations between Russia and [[Romania]].\n\nTMK GIPI employees of the Middle East Division are regular participants in blood donation campaigns in support of cancer, heart diseases and HIV sufferers.\n\nTMK's US Division acted as a leading corporate sponsor of the Age of Impressionism exhibition in the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|Museum of Fine Arts]], [[Houston]]. Support is also provided to charity organisations in the cities where the Division's entities operate, including the [[American Cancer Society]] and [[United Way Worldwide|United Way]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.tmk-group.com/ TMK Official Website]\n*[http://www.linkedin.com/companies/tmk/ TMK Company Profile, LinkedIn.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070926000331/http://www.artrom.ro/ TMK-ARTROM]\n*[http://www.steelbb.com/ Steel Business Briefing]\n*[http://www.metalbulletin.com.ru/ Metallurgical Bulletin]\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of Russian companies]]\n*[[South Stream]]\n*[[Nord Stream]] - planned gas pipeline between Russia and Germany\n*[[Shtokman field]]\n*[[Sakhalin-II]]\n*[[Burgas\u2013Alexandroupoli pipeline]]\n\n[[TMK (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n{{Moscow Exchange Index}}\n\n[[Category:Steel companies of Russia]]\n[[Category:Russian brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Moscow]]\n[[Category:Companies established in 2001]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Moscow Exchange]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Russia]]\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Chelyabiinsk->Chelyabinsk -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/OAO_TMK"}
{"title_page": "MG ZS SUV", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|Subcompact crossover SUV produced by MG Motor}}\n{{Distinguish|MG ZS}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = MG ZS\n| image = File:2018 MG ZS Exclusive 1.5 Front.jpg\n| caption = \n| type = \n| manufacturer = [[MG Motor]] ([[SAIC Motor]])\n| production = 2017\u2013present\n| model_years = \n| assembly = [[Lingang]], [[Shanghai]], [[China]] <br />[[Zhengzhou]], [[China]] (SAIC Motor Passenger Vehicle's Zhengzhou Plant)<br />[[Laem Chabang]], [[Thailand]] ([[SAIC Motor|SAIC]]-[[Charoen Pokphand Group|CP]])<br />[[Halol]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]] ([[MG Motor India]]) (EV)\n| designer = \n| class = [[Subcompact car|Subcompact]] [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover SUV]]\n| body_style = 5-door [[Compact sport utility vehicle|SUV]]\n| layout = [[Front-engine, front-wheel-drive layout|Front-engine, front-wheel-drive]]\n| platform = \n| related = [[Roewe RX3]]\n| engine = {{unbulleted list\n  | 1.5L VTI-Tech NSE Plus [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])\n  | 1.5L GM/SAIC SGE VTI-Tech NSE Plus ''15S4C'' [[Inline-four engine|I4]] ([[Petrol engine|petrol]])\n  | 1.0L [[GM small gasoline engine|GM/SAIC SGE]] ''[[Turbocharger|Turbo]] [[Gasoline direct injection|GDI]]'' [[Straight-three engine|I3]] (petrol)\n  | 1.3L GM/SAIC SGE ''[[Turbocharger|Turbo]] [[Gasoline direct injection|GDI]]'' [[Straight-three engine|I3]] (petrol)\n  }}\n| motor = Permanent Magnet Synchronous Electric Motor (MG ZS EV)\n| transmission = {{unbulleted list\n  | 5-speed [[Manual transmission|manual]]\n  | 4-speed [[Automatic transmission|automatic]]\n  | 6-speed Dual-clutch automatic\n  | 8-speed [[Continuously variable transmission|CVT]]\n  | e-[[Continuously variable transmission|CVT]] (MG ZS EV SUV)\n  }}\n| wheelbase = {{convert|2585|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| length = {{convert|4314|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| width = {{convert|1809|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| height = {{convert|1611|mm|in|1|abbr=on}}\n| weight = {{unbulleted list\n  |<!-- {{convert|NNNN|-|NNNN|kg|lb|0|abbr=on}} -->\n  }}\n| predecessor = \n| successor = \n| sp = uk\n| aka = MG ZX (Peru)\n}}\nThe '''MG ZS''' is a [[Subcompact car|subcompact]] [[Crossover (automobile)|crossover SUV]] produced by the Chinese owned, British automotive marque [[MG Motor]]. \n\nThe MG ZS is the second SUV to be produced by MG Motor, the first being the larger [[MG GS]], which was launched in April 2015. The MG ZS notably revives the name previously used on the saloon of the [[MG ZS]], which was based on the [[Rover 45]], and was produced by MG Motor's predecessors [[MG Rover Group|MG Rover]] from 2001 to 2005.\n\n==Overview==\n[[File:2020 MG ZS SUV bodykit in Brunei (interior).jpg|thumb|left|Interior]]\n[[File:2018 MG ZS Exclusive 1.5 Rear.jpg|thumb|left|Rear view]]\n[[File:MG ZS facelift 001.jpg|thumb|left|Facelift (2019)]]\nThe MG ZS was announced in 2016, at the Guangzhou Auto Show in China. The MG ZS marked MG Motor's second venture into the market of crossover/SUV. It is intended to sit below the larger MG GS, but larger than the smaller [[MG 3]].<ref>{{cite web|title=MG ZS SUV Launched On The Guangzhou Auto Show In China|url=https://www.carnewschina.com/2016/11/21/mg-zs-suv-launched-on-the-guangzhou-auto-show-in-china/|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref> The MG ZS was subsequently launched in China, in March 2017.\n\nThe MG ZS was announced at the [[London Motorfair|London Motor Show]] in May 2017 for the United Kingdom, and production commenced at the end of 2017. The MG ZS SUV was also shown at the [[Auto Shanghai]] Motor Show in April 2017, alongside the new concept, MG E Motion.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|title=Nissan Juke-rivalling MG ZS SUV shown at Shanghai motor show|url=https://www.autocar.co.uk/car-news/motor-shows-shanghai-auto-show/nissan-juke-rivalling-mg-zs-suv-shown-shanghai-motor-show|accessdate=20 April 2017}}</ref>\n\nTo avoid confusion with the previous [[MG ZS]], it was announced the ZS SUV was to be called ''XS'' in the United Kingdom, however this change of name did not occur, and to date, the model is still listed as the MG ZS on the website of MG Motors for the United Kingdom.\n\nIn Brunei, The ZS SUV was launched since the middle of 2019. The ZS SUV comes with two trims: COM and DEL. \n\nThe COM 1.5L VTI Tech NSE Plus I4 engine (paired with four speed automatic), folding key, fabric seats, eight inch touch screen interface with CarPlay and automatic air conditioning. and the DEL comes with 1.0L GDI I3 engine (paired with six speed automatic), panoramic sunroof and push start button only.\n\nAn [[Electric car|all electric]] version made its debut as EZS at the 2018 [[Guangzhou Auto Show]], and is now on sale in United Kingdom, Thailand, China, and The Netherlands. It is expected to go on sale in India in the beginning of 2020. Except for China, the electric SUV is officially named as ZS EV, while the official name in China is EZS.<ref>{{cite web|title=MG ZS electric SUV India launch postponed to early 2020|url=https://www.autodevot.com/2019/09/mg-zs-electric-suv-india-launch-postponed-2020/|work=autodevot.com|accessdate=1 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nA facelift of the crossover MG ZS was revealed in 2019 in China, featuring a redesigned front fascia, now disconnecting the lamps from the grilles, and deleting the chrome trim around the grilles.\n\nA facelift of the crossover MG ZS was revealed in 24 March 2020 in Thailand, featuring 1.5L SAIC NetBlue Blue Core Power Technology I4 engine, 8-speed CVT stepless, along with a package of driver assistance systems, six airbags and a 360 degree view monitor.\n\n==Engines==\nThe ZS has two [[petrol engine]]s options, an updated SMTC developed version of the naturally aspirated 1.5 L as found in the MG3, known in this guise as the NSE Plus (formerly just NSE) the updated engine is tuned differently in each market based on locally applicable emission regulations. \n\nIn China, for example, the engine is tuned to deliver 120 PS and 150 Nm torque. In the United Kingdom, where the emission regulations are more strict, the engine delivers 106 PS and 141 Nm of torque. \n\nThe second engine is a new turbocharged three cylinder engine, developed by [[SAIC Motor|SAIC]] in conjunction with [[General Motors]]. Again in China, it produces 125 PS and 175 Nm torque, but in the United Kingdom, it produces 111 PS and 160 Nm torque.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==MG EZS==\nThe MG EZS is the electric version of the MG ZS. The MG EZS was introduced in 2019 in China, featuring a 44.5 kWh battery, and a front positioned motor producing 110&nbsp;kW and 350 Nm to the front wheels.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ev-database.uk/car/1201/MG-ZS-EV|title=MG ZS EV|website=EV Database|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-10-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=NMG EZS specs|url=https://car.autohome.com.cn/config/series/4948.html#pvareaid=3454437|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref> \n\nMG has announced that the EZS will be sold in United Kingdom, Thailand, India, Australia and New Zealand as the MG ZS EV being the first Chinese EV SUV to enter those markets.<ref>https://newatlas.com/mg-e-zs-electric/59456/</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|Fastcharge Port\n|[[Combined Charging System|CCS]]\n|-\n|Fastcharge Power (max)\n|60 kW DC\n|-\n| Standard Charge\n|[[Type 2 connector|Type 2]]\n|-\n|Charge Power\n|7.4 kW AC\n|}\nThe MG EZS scored a five star safety rating in the crash tests organised by [[Euro NCAP]] in December 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://in.vroomhead.com/mg-zs-ev-five-star-euro-ncap-crash-test-rating/|title=MG ZS EV Scores 5 Star Rating In Euro NCAP Crash Test|date=2019-12-18|website=in.vroomhead.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-21}}</ref><gallery widths=\"220px\">\nFile:MG EZS 02 China 2019-04-03.jpg|MG EZS (electric crossover)\nFile:MG EZS 05 China 2019-04-03.jpg|MG EZS (electric crossover)\n</gallery>\n\n==Sales==\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|-\n! Calendar Year\n!China<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://carsalesbase.com/china-car-sales-data/mg/mg-zs/|title=MG ZS China auto sales figures|website=carsalesbase.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n! Thailand\n!United Kingdom<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://carsalesbase.com/european-car-sales-data/saic-mg/mg-zs/|title=MG ZS European and UK sales figures|website=carsalesbase.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-20}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2017\n|70,164\n| 768<ref name=\"Thailand cars sales report 2017\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.headlightmag.com/sales-report-december-2017/ |title=Thailand cars sales report 2017 |work=HeadlightMag.com |location=Thailand |access-date=24 October 2018}}</ref>\n|374\n|-\n| 2018\n|112,159\n|14,669<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.headlightmag.com/sales-report-teaser-b-suv-dec-2018/|title= 2018 Thailand B-SUV sales report|location=Thailand |access-date=7 March 2019}}</ref>\n|5,376\n|-\n| 2019\n|121,972\n|14,410 (ZS + ZS EV)\n|9,872\n|-\n|}\n\n{{clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|MG ZS (China)}}\n*{{Official website|https://www.mgmotor.me/new-cars/zs/}}\n{{MG Motor}}{{MG timeline 2000 to date|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:MG vehicles|GS]]\n[[Category:Cars introduced in 2015]]\n[[Category:2020s cars]]\n[[Category:Cars of China]]\n[[Category:Crossover sport utility vehicles]]\n[[Category:Front-wheel-drive vehicles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{short description|Subcompact crossover SUV produced by MG Motor}}\n{{Distinguish|MG ZS}}\n\n{{Infobox automobile\n| name = MG ZS\n| image = File:2018 MG ZS Exclusive 1.5 Front.jpg\n| caption = \n| type = \n| manufacturer = [[MG Motor]] ([[SAIC Motor]])\n| production = 2017\u2013present\n| model_years = \n| assembly = [[Lingang]], [[Shanghai]], [[China]] <br />[[Zhengzhou]], [[China]] (SAIC Motor Passenger Vehicle's Zhengzhou Plant)<br />[[Laem Chabang]], [[Thailand]] ([[SAIC Motor|SAIC]]-[[Charoen Pokphand Group|CP]])<br />[[Halol]], [[Gujarat]], [[India]] ([[MG Motor India]]) (EV)\n|